{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527762"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14223"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14223"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.06,0.2,0.13,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6910"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42509"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"2400"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"3006"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44408"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the Respiratory Medicine clinic with a three-week history of persistent cough without productive sputum, and occasional haemoptysis. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis for which she is on long-term immunosuppressants. She does not smoke and has no recent travel history. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A chest X-ray is taken (see image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Emphysematous bulla","Lung cancer","Tuberculosis","Lung abscess","Aspergilloma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a chest X-ray revealing a cavitating lesion in the right upper lobe and a history of immunosuppression, which raises the suspicion of an opportunistic infection. The clinical presentation and imaging findings are suggestive of an \u003Cstrong\u003Easpergilloma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a fungal ball, which typically forms in pre-existing lung cavities, especially in immunocompromised individuals. Aspergillomas are often seen in patients with a history of lung diseases, but can also occur in those with immunosuppression. On chest X-ray, an aspergilloma appears as a round mass within a pre-existing cavity, often with an air crescent sign indicating the presence of air between the fungal ball and the cavity wall. The air crescent sign is a radiological finding where a crescent of air can be seen outlining the upper part of the fungal ball within the cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of aspergilloma may involve antifungal therapy, such as voriconazole, and in some cases, surgical resection if there is significant haemoptysis or risk of complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elung abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility, but it is usually associated with a history of aspiration or bacterial infection. Lung abscesses often present with systemic symptoms such as fever and malaise, which are not described in this patient. The absence of these symptoms and the patient\u0027s immunosuppressed state make aspergilloma more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause cavitating lesions, but the absence of risk factors such as recent travel or known exposure, along with the patient\u0027s immunosuppressed state, makes aspergilloma a more probable diagnosis. Additionally, tuberculosis often presents with systemic symptoms like night sweats and weight loss, which are not mentioned here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E can present with cavitating lesions, but the patient\u0027s clinical history points towards an infectious cause. Lung cancer is less likely given the absence of smoking history and the presence of immunosuppression, which predisposes to infections rather than malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eemphysematous bulla\u003C/strong\u003E is a large air-filled space within the lung parenchyma, typically seen in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). It does not usually present with haemoptysis or a fungal ball appearance on imaging. The patient\u0027s history of immunosuppression and the presence of a cavitating lesion with haemoptysis make an aspergilloma more likely than an emphysematous bulla.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aspergillus-related cavitating lesions in the lung can occur in immunocompromised patients, such as those on immunosuppressants for rheumatoid arthritis.","Chest X-ray findings for patients with aspergilloma may include a cavitating lesion in one of the lung lobes, and an air crescent sign indicating the presence of air between the fungal ball and the cavity wall."],"references":["Chakraborty RK, Gilotra TS, Tobin EH, et al. Aspergilloma. [Updated 2024 Jan 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546668/","Youssef C, Widlus DM. Imaging diagnosis of aspergilloma. J Community Hosp Intern Med Perspect. 2012 Apr 30;2(1). doi: 10.3402/jchimp.v2i1.17276. PMID: 23882357; PMCID: PMC3714090.","Kousha M, Tadi R, Soubani AO. Pulmonary aspergillosis: a clinical review. Eur Respir Rev. 2011 Sep 1;20(121):156-74. doi: 10.1183/09059180.00001011. PMID: 21881144; PMCID: PMC9584108.","Fred HL, Gardiner CL. The air crescent sign: causes and characteristics. Tex Heart Inst J. 2009;36(3):264-5. PMID: 19568404; PMCID: PMC2696502.","Lamoth F, Calandra T. Pulmonary aspergillosis: diagnosis and treatment. Eur Respir Rev. 2022 Nov 29;31(166):220114. doi: 10.1183/16000617.0114-2022. PMID: 36450372; PMCID: PMC9724826."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42509"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14223"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21033"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21033"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bXG4du97BTYuv6u9lk9fcGtKUvN4Xu.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bXG4du97BTYuv6u9lk9fcGtKUvN4Xu.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":872,"height":884}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42509"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T10:02:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T12:22:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6910"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57054"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"